1 Quick Review on the Theory

1.1 LDA

  • Consider data \((\mathbf{x}_i,y_i), i=1,\dots,n\), where \(\mathbf{x}_i \in \mathbb{R}^p\) and \(y_i\in \{1,2,\dots,K\}\). Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) assumes that \(\mathbf{X}|Y=k \sim N(\boldsymbol{\mu}_k,\Sigma)\). Furthermore, the prior probability of \(Y\) is \(p(Y=k) = \pi_k\). The LDA method estimates the parameters \(\boldsymbol{\mu}_k,\pi_k,\Sigma\) for all \(k\), denoted as \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}_k,\hat{\pi}_k,\hat{\Sigma}\). And classify any new data point \(\mathbf{x}_i^{*}\) based on the Bayes rule:

\[ C(\mathbf{x}_i^{*}) = \underset{k}{\operatorname{argmax}} \hat{\pi}_k\cdot \hat{f}(\mathbf{x}_i|y_i=k) \]

  • The method is entitled with linear because the decision boundary is linear (hyperplane). For example:

\[ \log \frac{p(y=k|\mathbf{x})}{p(y=l|\mathbf{x})} = \log \frac{\pi_k}{\pi_l} - \frac12 (\boldsymbol{\mu}_k + \boldsymbol{\mu}_l)^{T}\Sigma^{-1}(\boldsymbol{\mu}_k - \boldsymbol{\mu}_l) + \mathbf{x}^T\Sigma^{-1}(\boldsymbol{\mu}_k-\boldsymbol{\mu}_l) \]

  • The above quantity, when equals to zero, defines the decision boundary spliting classes k and l. And it is linear in terms of \(\mathbf{x}\). The vector \(\Sigma^{-1}(\boldsymbol{\mu}_k-\boldsymbol{\mu}_l)\) is called discriminant direction. Note that in practice, the decision boundary should have the estimated \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}_k,\hat{\pi}_k,\hat{\Sigma}\) in place of \(\boldsymbol{\mu}_k,\pi_k,\Sigma\).

  • Number of parameters to estimate: \(K-1\) (class prior) + \(K\cdot p\) (class mean) + \(p(p+1)/2\) (shared covariance matrix).

  • Estimation of all parameters requires that in aggregate, we have a sample size \(n > p\).

1.2 QDA

  • Similar to LDA, quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA) also assumes a normal distribution on \(X|Y=k\). The only difference is that \(\mathbf{X}|Y=k \sim N(\boldsymbol{\mu}_k,\Sigma_k)\), where the covariance matrix is no longer shared across different conditional densities. It is called quadratic because the decision boundary is a quadratic form of \(\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\).

  • Number of parameters to estimate: \(K-1\) (class prior) + \(K\cdot p\) (class mean) + \(K\cdot p(p+1)/2\) (class-specific covariance matrix).

  • Estimation of class-specific covariance matrix requires that for each group, we have a sample size \(n_k > p\).

1.3 Naive Bayes

  • Similar to the setup of LDA and QDA, we have data \((\mathbf{x}_i,y_i), i=1,\dots,n\), where \(\mathbf{x}_i \in \mathbb{R}^p\) and \(y_i\in \{1,2,\dots,K\}\). But Naive Bayes (NB) assumes conditional independence of predictors of \(\mathbf{x}_i\) given \(y_i\):

\[ f(x_1,x_2,\dots,x_p|y) = f(x_1|y)\cdot f(x_2|y) \cdot \dots\cdot f(x_p|y) \] where \((x_1,x_2,\dots,x_p)\) is a feature vector.

  • Typically, the conditional density above is further assumed to be jointly normal. Given this normality assumption, NB is a simplified LDA with a diagonal \(\Sigma\) matrix (zero correlation between variables due to conditional independence).

  • Number of parameters to estimate: \(K-1\) (class prior) + \(K\cdot p\) (class mean) + \(p\) (diagonal covariance matrix). NB has much fewer number of parameters compared to LDA and QDA when p is large.

  • When \(p\) is large, typically for bias: NB > LDA > QDA, and for variance: QDA > LDA > NB.

2 Programming with R

2.1 Preparations

2.1.1 Data and Train-test-split

We will use the iris dataset to illustrate LDA and QDA. Species is a three-level categorical variable. We will use it as the target of classification.

We will split each class proportionately for training and testing. We will take 70% of the Setosa irises, 70% of the Virginica irises, and 70% of the Versicolor irises to be in the training set.

set.seed(123) # for reproducibility
table(iris$Species)
## 
##     setosa versicolor  virginica 
##         50         50         50
iris_setosa = which(iris$Species == "setosa")
iris_versi = which(iris$Species == "versicolor")
iris_virg = which(iris$Species == "virginica")
train_id = c(sample(iris_setosa, size = trunc(0.70 * length(iris_setosa))),
             sample(iris_versi, size = trunc(0.70 * length(iris_versi))),
             sample(iris_virg, size = trunc(0.70 * length(iris_virg))))
iris_train = iris[train_id, ]
iris_test = iris[-train_id, ]

2.1.2 Data Visualization

Lets explore the training data graphically to examine the relationship between Species and the other variables. Remember that our target is Species. This is a categorical variable! So we will use different colors or symbols to distinguish them in the plots.

pairs(iris_train[1:4], col=c("blue", "green","red")[iris_train$Species], 
      pch=c(1,2,3)[iris_train$Species])
par(xpd=TRUE)
legend(0.34, 0.71, as.vector(unique(iris_train$Species)), 
       col=c("blue", "green", "red"), pch=1:3, cex = 0.5)

  • par(xpd=TRUE) is just a graphical option that allows us to easily place the legend on this pairs scatterplot. Try commenting it out and running this chunk. Youll notice that the legend fails to appear. (This is not super important to know.)
  • Positioning the legend can be a little tricky. Fiddle with the first two arguments to place it in a good spot.

2.2 LDA

2.2.1 Fit lda model

To fit an LDA model, we use the lda() function from the MASS package.

library(MASS)                                  # loads the MASS package
iris_lda = lda(Species ~ ., data = iris_train) # trains LDA model using iris_train
iris_lda                                       # look at the LDA model
## Call:
## lda(Species ~ ., data = iris_train)
## 
## Prior probabilities of groups:
##     setosa versicolor  virginica 
##  0.3333333  0.3333333  0.3333333 
## 
## Group means:
##            Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width
## setosa         4.991429    3.365714     1.471429   0.2314286
## versicolor     5.942857    2.777143     4.262857   1.3285714
## virginica      6.631429    2.982857     5.591429   2.0342857
## 
## Coefficients of linear discriminants:
##                     LD1         LD2
## Sepal.Length  0.8603517 -0.02531284
## Sepal.Width   1.3884435 -2.37490707

## Petal.Width  -2.9135037 -2.68733735

2.2.2 Visualize the linear discriminant

plot(iris_lda, col = as.integer(iris_train$Species))

2.2.3 Visualize the partition with klaR package

# install.packages("klaR") # please install it if you have not
library(klaR)
partimat(Species ~ Sepal.Length + Sepal.Width + Petal.Length + Petal.Width, data=iris_train, method="lda")

2.2.4 Predict the test data

The predict() function operates in a new way when called on an lda object. By default, it returns an entire list. Within that list class stores the class predictions and posterior contains the estimated posterior probability for each class. If we want to extract the predictions or posterior probability estimates, we can do that with the $ notation.

names(predict(iris_lda, iris_test))
## [1] "class"     "posterior" "x"
head(predict(iris_lda, iris_test)$class, n = 9)
## [1] setosa setosa setosa setosa setosa setosa setosa setosa setosa
## Levels: setosa versicolor virginica
head(predict(iris_lda, iris_test)$posterior, n = 9)
##    setosa   versicolor    virginica
## 1       1 5.180307e-23 7.105444e-45
## 2       1 6.112832e-19 7.524191e-40
## 6       1 1.222997e-21 4.908094e-42
## 16      1 5.033088e-28 2.899621e-50
## 18      1 6.497181e-22 4.190740e-43
## 20      1 5.979798e-23 3.701092e-44
## 22      1 3.519153e-21 1.376569e-41
## 23      1 8.279076e-26 1.719910e-48
## 34      1 3.843511e-29 1.589131e-52
lda.test = predict(iris_lda, iris_test)
iris_test$lda = lda.test$class
table(predicted = iris_test$lda, actual = iris_test$Species)
##             actual
## predicted    setosa versicolor virginica
##   setosa         15          0         0
##   versicolor      0         15         1
##   virginica       0          0        14

2.2.5 Training and testing error

We just fit an LDA model (iris_lda). Now lets make predictions (for both the training and test observations):

iris_lda_train_pred = predict(iris_lda, iris_train)$class
iris_lda_test_pred = predict(iris_lda, iris_test)$class

To calculate training and test error, do

train_err = mean(iris_lda_train_pred != iris_train$Species)
test_err = mean(iris_lda_test_pred != iris_test$Species)
train_err
## [1] 0.01904762
test_err
## [1] 0.02222222

iris_qda_test_pred = predict(iris_qda, iris_test)$class

Heres the training error, test error, and confusion matrix:

train_err = mean(iris_qda_train_pred != iris_train$Species)

2.4 Naive Bayes

2.4.1 About Data

We use hsbdemo dataset to try this method. The dataset contains variables on 200 students. The outcome variable is prog, program type: academic/general/vacational. The features contains the scores of several subjects, such as reading, writing, math, science, social science and others like sex, school type, social economic status, honors, awards. We are interested in how well we can predict a students program type using these related features.

We remove the id and cid from the columns, since they cannot be meaningful predictors.

mydata <- mydata[,-1]
mydata <- mydata[,-ncol(mydata)]

2.4.1.2 Train-test-split

We will make a 70/30 partitioning for the training and test set.

set.seed(231)
mydata_general = which(mydata$prog=="general")
mydata_academic = which(mydata$prog=="academic")
mydata_vocation = which(mydata$prog=="vocation")
trainIndex = c(sample(mydata_general, size = trunc(0.70 * length(mydata_general))),
             sample(mydata_academic, size = trunc(0.70 * length(mydata_academic))),
             sample(mydata_vocation, size = trunc(0.70 * length(mydata_vocation))))
train=mydata[trainIndex, ]
test=mydata[-trainIndex, ]

2.4.2 Fit NB model with e1071 package

Next, we use the training data to fit the Naive Bayes classifier using science and math as predictors

library(e1071)
NBclassfier=naiveBayes(prog~science+math, data=train)
print(NBclassfier)
## 
## Naive Bayes Classifier for Discrete Predictors
## 
## Call:
## naiveBayes.default(x = X, y = Y, laplace = laplace)
## 
## A-priori probabilities:
## Y
##   general  academic  vocation 
## 0.2230216 0.5251799 0.2517986 
## 
## Conditional probabilities:
##           science
## Y              [,1]      [,2]
##   general  51.87097  9.807283
##   academic 53.49315  9.453282
##   vocation 47.97143 10.942324
## 
##           math
## Y              [,1]     [,2]
##   general  49.19355 7.082464
##   academic 56.39726 8.926770
##   vocation 47.22857 8.506350

The naiveBayes function assumed gaussian distributions for numeric varibles. Also, the priori are calculated from the porportion of the training data. The prioris are shown when the object is printed. The Y values are the means and standard deviations of the predictors within each class.

Now, lets make predictions on training and test data and calculate the errors for both.

pred_train = predict(NBclassfier,newdata = train)
mean(pred_train!=train$prog)
## [1] 0.4244604
pred_test = predict(NBclassfier,newdata = test)
mean(pred_test!=test$prog)
## [1] 0.4098361

2.4.3 Refit NB with more predictors

Fit NB with more predictors can improve performances. Note how binary variable schtyp is modeled as Bernoulli instead of Gaussian.
